      title: "The Brochure",
      synopsis: "",
      text: `<div class="reading-font text-gray-300">
    <p class="mb-6">March. The smell of almost-spring, which in Millhaven meant mud and possibility in equal measure.<br>They were at their table — the six of them, lunch, ordinary — when Marcus put both hands flat on the table with the energy of someone who had made a decision and needed witnesses.<br>"We need to do something," he said. "This summer. All six of us. Before everything."<br>"You've said this before," Priya said, without looking up.<br>"I'm saying it more specifically now." He looked around the table. "Last summer together. We should — mark it somehow. Do something we'll remember."<br>"We'll remember everything," Danny said, with the confidence of someone who has not yet experienced how much adulthood erases.<br>"We won't," Simone said. "We'll remember the things we can tell stories about. We need something storyable."<br>"A trip," Theo said.<br>"A real one," Marcus said. "Not just somewhere to sit. Somewhere with a — a structure. Something to do."<br>"A challenge," Priya said, and something lit up in her that she tried to moderate because she was aware of how she looked when she said the word challenge. She looked the way she looked. She couldn't help it.
    <br>Jodelle, who had been drawing for the past several minutes with the focused quiet of someone running slightly parallel to the conversation, reached into the front pocket of her bag and slid a folded brochure across the table without preamble.<br>She went back to drawing.<br>They looked at the brochure.<br>It was folded and unfolded so many times that the creases were soft, the paper worn at the corners. On the cover: a photograph of a glacial lake through pine trees, a wooden dock, a sky that had been caught on a perfect day. CAMP ALDERMOOR — Senior Leadership and Adventure Program. Ages 16–18. Summer Residential.<br>Marcus unfolded it. Read. Passed it to Priya. She read faster, passed it to Simone. Danny looked at the pictures. Theo read it properly.<br>"How long have you had this?" Marcus said.<br>"A while," Jodelle said.<br>"Why?"<br>She looked up from her drawing. "My dad found it last year. He thought it sounded structured, which is what he looks for. I told him I wasn't going." She returned to her drawing. "I changed my mind."<br>"When?" Priya said.<br>A pause. "February."<br>Simone looked at her. February was when the dream had happened — the clearing, the stone building, the man at the northeast corner. She said nothing.<br>"It's in the woods," Danny said, still looking at the photographs with the enthusiasm of someone who had never camped and considered this irrelevant. "There's a lake. And look — there's a treasure hunt thing."<br>"Team-based," Priya said, already reading the details. "Multi-day. Progressive clues. They don't tell you the final location."<br>"That's irritating," Marcus said, which meant he was interested.<br>"There's an orienteering component," Theo said. "Overnight hiking. Map reading.
    "<br>"Cabins," Danny said. "Not tents. Important."<br>"Two weeks," Simone said. "Mid-July."<br>They all looked at each other with the specific look of six people doing simultaneous mental calculations about parents, money, other plans, and the particular weight of last summer pressing down on all of it.<br>"I'll make a spreadsheet," Priya said, which was how she said yes.<br>"Obviously I'm in," Marcus said.<br>"Me too," Danny said, already picturing the lake.<br>"I'll need to check the dates," Simone said, which was how she said yes.<br>"Okay," Theo said, which was how he said everything.<br>They looked at Jodelle. She was still drawing. She had been drawing, the whole conversation, in the way she did when she was paying close attention to something — more focused, not less.<br>"Jo," Marcus said. "You're the one who brought the brochure."<br>"I know," she said.<br>"So that's a yes."<br>She looked up then, and for a moment she was completely present — all of her, in the room, at the table, looking at the five of them with something that was warm and specific and a little like she was memorizing them.<br>"Yes," she said. "I'm going."<br>Theo looked at her. Then at the brochure. At the photograph of the lake.<br>I think I was always going to go there.<br>He remembered her saying it, months ago, when it had still been hypothetical. He thought about the dream she'd described. The clearing. The stone foundation. The northeast corner.<br>He picked up the brochure and folded it carefully along its worn lines and handed it back to her.<br>She tucked it into her bag.<br>Outside, March did its uncertain thing — cold and warm in alternating minutes, the light changing every time you looked up. Senior year rolled forward. The table held its six.<br>For now. For a little while yet.</p>
</div>`
