      text: `<div class="reading-font text-gray-300">
    <p class="mb-6">The offices of Hargreave & Associates were on the ground floor of a Victorian building on Commerce Street, three doors down from the Italian restaurant. The building had good bones and indifferent maintenance — the kind of legal office that communicates established rather than thriving.<br>R. Hargreave turned out to be a woman — mid-sixties, precise, with the contained energy of someone who has been holding something for a long time and is ready to put it down. She welcomed them into a conference room with a long table and five chairs arranged on one side of it, facing her, which Priya noted and which felt significant.<br>Five chairs. Arranged for five people.<br>Prepared.<br>"Thank you for coming," Hargreave said, when they were seated. "I understand this was not a simple request to fulfill. I appreciate the effort."<br>She placed a folder on the table. She looked at the five of them — across the table, across eleven years — with the expression of someone who knows more than they're going to say and has made their peace with that.<br>"Mr. and Mrs. Vasquez retained my services in 2019," she said. "Mrs. Vasquez was already unwell by that point, though she was lucid and specific about her wishes. Mr. Vasquez added several provisions after Mrs. Vasquez passed this February. The will is therefore a joint document with amendments."<br>She opened the folder.<br>"The estate is modest. The house on Birchwood Lane, some savings, personal effects. The house is to be sold, the proceeds divided as detailed in the will. That is the conventional portion."<br>She turned a page.<br>"The unconventional portion." She looked up. "Mr. and Mrs. Vasquez were specific, detailed, and — in my professional assessment — extremely purposeful about what they wanted to happen." A pause. "They were Jodelle's parents. I was acquainted with them only through this work, but I will say: they were people who thought carefully about things. Who planned at a significant distance."<br>"How long have you known about us?" Marcus said.<br>"Since 2019," Hargreave said. "When they first came in, they gave me your names and addresses and asked me to keep the file current. I've been maintaining it for four years."<br>Four years. They had been tracked, carefully and distantly, for four years.<br>"What do they want?" Priya said. Straight, direct. The way she asked diagnostic questions.<br>Hargreave turned another page.<br>"They want your children to go to Camp Aldermoor," she said.<br>The room was completely still.<br>"The camp," Simone said.<br>"The camp," Hargreave confirmed. "Which is now operated, in its summer program, under the auspices of a charitable trust established by the Vasquez estate and several co-donors I am not at liberty to name, though you may draw your own conclusions." She turned a page. "The summer program for the year following the reading of this will is a two-week residential program for children aged eight to fourteen. The trust has allocated five places — one for each of your children — at no cost to you."<br>"Our children," Danny said.<br>"All of whom," Hargreave said, "are named Jodelle."<br>She said it without inflection. Without drama. The fact simply arriving.<br>"They knew," Marcus said. Not a question.<br>"They have known since — " She checked her notes. "Since 2015, when the first daughter was born. They had been following your lives at a distance. They were not — " She paused, choosing carefully. "They were not angry, I want to be clear about that. They were not pursuing any legal course. They simply — watched. And when the pattern became clear, they incorporated it into what they wanted to do."<br>"Five daughters named Jodelle," Priya said.<br>"Five daughters named Jodelle," Hargreave confirmed. "They considered this — significant."<br>"What did they want from this?" Theo said. "The camp. The children together. What was the purpose?"<br>Hargreave looked at him. She seemed, for a moment, to consider how much of her own assessment to include.<br>"I think," she said carefully, "they believed that guilt kept in silence calcifies. That it becomes permanent and structural. And that the best — the only — way to release it was to create a situation in which it had to become something else."<br>The table absorbed this.<br>"They're not punishing us," Simone said slowly.<br>"No," Hargreave said. "I don't believe so."<br>"They're giving us a way out," Marcus said.<br>Hargreave looked at him. "I believe they are giving your children a way in," she said. "Which may amount to the same thing."<br>She placed a sealed envelope on the table. For when the children have been to camp, it read, in handwriting that was old and deliberate and careful.<br>"This is to be opened," she said, "after the summer program concludes. Not before."<br>They looked at the envelope.<br>Five people. One envelope. Eleven years of silence sitting in the room like a sixth chair that nobody had sat in.<br>"They planned this," Danny said. "For years. Even while—"<br>"Yes," Hargreave said.<br>"Why?" Danny said. "Why would they — after what we — "<br>Hargreave looked at him with an expression that was both professional and human, the exact calibration of someone who has spent a long time thinking about the right thing to say.<br>"Because," she said, "their daughter loved you. All of you. Completely." She paused. "And they loved their daughter."</p>
</div>`
