      text: `<div class="reading-font text-gray-300">
    
    <blockquote class="border-l-2 border-[#d4af37] pl-4 py-2 my-8 italic text-[#d4af37]/80">Meera — Age 9 — (Jodelle Meera Nair)</blockquote>
    <p class="mb-6">The solicitor's office smelled like old paper and something that might have been a cat but no cat was visible, which I thought was suspicious.<br>Mum had told me to sit quietly and read my book, which I was doing, but I was also listening, which she hadn't said I couldn't do. The adults were in a room with a closed door and I was in the waiting area on a hard chair with my book and the maybe-cat smell and a water cooler that made a sound every four minutes. I timed it.<br>There were four other kids in the waiting area.<br>I noticed them the way I notice things — systematically, from the edges inward. Oldest to youngest, I thought, though it was hard to tell with some of them.<br>The oldest was a girl of maybe thirteen or fourteen, sitting very straight with a book of her own, reading with the specific focused quality of someone who is using reading as a reason not to look at anyone. Her hair was dark and she had rings on some of her fingers — not many, two or three — and she was wearing a dark blue cardigan that was slightly too big for her.<br>The second was a girl of maybe eleven, who had a notebook open and was writing in it. Not the loose scribbling of someone bored — careful, deliberate, organized. She glanced up every so often and I caught her looking at each of us in turn with an expression I recognized as the same one I had, which was: I am mapping this room.<br>Then there was a boy — except it wasn't a boy, it was a girl with short hair who was sitting with one knee up and the other leg extended, texting on a phone with absolute focus. She looked about my age, maybe a year older.<br>And the youngest was a small girl — five, maybe six — sitting very still with her hands in her lap, looking at the water cooler. Not the way bored children look at things, which is glazed and inward. She was watching it the way you watch something you're trying to understand. When it made its sound at the four-minute mark she nodded, as if confirming something.<br>I looked at the oldest girl again. The rings. The dark cardigan.<br>I looked at my own hands. I was wearing one ring — it had been my grandmother's, my mum's mother — a silver one on my middle finger.<br>"Do your parents know each other?" I said. To the room. To all four of them.<br>The oldest looked up from her book.<br>The one with the notebook kept writing but tilted her head.<br>The one with the phone looked up.<br>The little one turned from the water cooler and looked at me.<br>"I don't think so," the oldest said. "My mum seemed surprised when she saw your mum."<br>"They know each other," the notebook girl said, without looking up. "They just haven't seen each other in a long time. You can tell by the way adults pretend not to recognize someone when they actually do. There's a specific thing their faces do."<br>A short silence.<br>"What thing?" I asked.<br>"Their expressions go very controlled very quickly," she said. "Like they're putting on a neutral face in a hurry." She looked up. "All four of our parents did it when we walked in."<br>"All five," the oldest corrected. "Your dad did it too."<br>"My dad does it at the grocery store when he sees anyone from before," the phone girl said. "I thought it was just him. Is your name Jodelle?"<br>Silence.<br>Very complete silence.<br>The water cooler made its sound.<br>"Yes," the oldest said.<br>"Yes," the notebook girl said.<br>"Yes," I said.<br>"Obviously," the phone girl said.<br>The little one turned back to look at all of us. "Mine too," she said. "I'm Clara. I go by Clara."<br>We looked at each other.<br>Five girls in a solicitor's waiting room in Millhaven, Wisconsin, all named Jodelle.<br>"This is very strange," the oldest said. She said it with the calm of someone who has decided that stating the obvious is more useful than pretending it isn't.<br>"Our parents all knew the same person," the notebook girl said. "Someone named Jodelle who is dead. I think that's why we're all called it."<br>"How do you know she's dead?" the phone girl said.<br>"Because we're at a will reading. And because our parents look like people who've been carrying something for a long time." She closed the notebook. "And because my mum has a notebook she's never shown me. With observations in it. I found it once — I wasn't snooping, it fell. I only read three lines. The third line said Jodelle does not sleep at consistent hours." She paused. "My mum is a doctor. She only writes things down if they're data points."<br>Nobody said anything for a moment.<br>"Sophie," the oldest said. "I'm Sophie. Jodelle Sophia. My dad calls me Sophie. I think the Jodelle part is — separate. Something he keeps to himself."<br>"Meera," I said. "Jodelle Meera."<br>"Emma," the phone girl said. "Jodelle Emma. My dad runs. Every morning. He says it's for fitness. Mum says it's for something else."<br>"Jodi," the second-youngest said. "My mum makes films. She never shows us the old ones."<br>"Clara," the youngest said again. She was still looking at us with that watching expression. "My dad's an architect. He designs things so people feel safe inside them." A pause. "He says that's important. That the structure holds."<br>We sat with this.<br>"So we have to figure out what happened," Emma said.<br>"Obviously," Sophie said.<br>"How?" Meera said.<br>Sophie looked at the closed door. "Not today," she said. "Today we listen and we watch." She looked at each of us in turn — a look that was calm and specific and older than thirteen. "We don't tell them we've figured out the connection. Not yet."<br>"Why not?" Jodi asked.<br>"Because adults do better with things they have time to prepare for," Sophie said. "If we ask today, in a solicitor's office, they'll panic and we won't get the real answer." She paused. "We wait. We find the right place to ask."<br>"And where's that?" I said.<br>The door opened. Five adults came out.<br>They looked at each other. Then they looked at us.<br>Five of them. Five of us. All named Jodelle.<br>Something passed across my mother's face — the controlled expression, going neutral in a hurry, exactly like Sophie said.<br>But underneath the control — just for a second, just at the edges — something else. Something that looked like a door opening onto a room that had been closed for a very long time.<br>"The camp," Sophie said quietly, to all of us, as the adults began the careful choreography of collecting their children without making eye contact with each other. "That's where we ask."</p>
    <div class="text-center text-[#d4af37]/40 my-8 tracking-widest">✦ ✦ ✦</div>
    <p class="mb-6">
    <blockquote class="border-l-2 border-[#d4af37] pl-4 py-2 my-8 italic text-[#d4af37]/80">Sophie — Age 13 — (Jodelle Sophia Chen)</blockquote><br>My dad reads. I know people say their parents read but my dad reads — it's what he does the way other parents run or cook or watch sports. He reads and he edits other people's reading and when he's not doing either of those things he is thinking about them.<br>I read too. We're the same in that way.<br>But there are books on his shelf that I've noticed he's never read — or never re-read, which for him is the same thing. A shelf in his office, not prominent, not arranged with the careful specificity of the other shelves. These books are just there, slightly apart, like they've been put somewhere to be kept rather than to be used.<br>I've never asked about them. I've learned — the way you learn things about your parents, slowly, from a distance, like watching weather — that there are some shelves you don't ask about.<br>His face when he opened the letter from Hargreave & Associates was the face of someone reading something they have been expecting for a long time. Not surprised. Arrived at.<br>I read fast and I was watching from the doorway.<br>He sat down on the kitchen floor. My dad, who is composed and specific and carries himself like someone whose posture was decided a long time ago, sat down on the kitchen floor in his coat and stayed there.<br>I went and made tea and brought it to him without saying anything, the way he makes tea for me when something has happened at school that I don't want to talk about yet. He accepted it. We sat on the kitchen floor for a while.<br>"Dad," I said, eventually.<br>"Mm."<br>"Is it okay?"<br>He thought about this with the seriousness he gives all questions. "I think it's necessary," he said, which is different from okay, and which I understood.<br>The solicitor's office. The waiting room. The four other girls.<br>I had known as soon as we walked in. Four other families, four other girls around my age, in a solicitor's waiting room in a town my dad had never taken me to, never mentioned by name, never returned to in my entire life. The math was simple. I did it in the thirty seconds before I sat down.<br>The youngest — Clara — was watching the water cooler with an expression I recognized from mirrors. The kind of expression that means: I am paying attention to something that will matter later.<br>We introduced ourselves and it confirmed what I already knew.<br>Five Jodelles.<br>I organized them the way I organize things I need to understand — by what they offered and what they held back. Meera: precise, data-oriented, trained by a mother who keeps notebooks. Emma: fast, social, uses humor to approach difficult things from the side. Jodi: watchful, warm, asks the questions everyone else has and nobody has said. Clara: quiet, attending, not missing anything.<br>I was the oldest. This felt like a responsibility.<br>The camp had been in the will. Hargreave told us in the car park afterward, while the adults stood in a cluster talking in the low voices adults use when they're saying the true version of something — Dad's voice had a quality in it I hadn't heard before, a kind of thinness, like whatever he was made of had been stretched. She told the five of us, standing slightly to the side, that we'd been allocated places at the summer program at Camp Aldermoor. Together. Two weeks in July.<br>"It's the same camp," Emma said.<br>"Obviously," I said.<br>"Why there?" Jodi said.<br>I thought about the way my dad had sat down on the kitchen floor. About the books he's never re-read. About the shelf that holds things to be kept rather than used.<br>"Because that's where it happened," I said. "Whatever happened. That's where we're going to find it."</p>
    <div class="text-center text-[#d4af37]/40 my-8 tracking-widest">✦ ✦ ✦</div>
    <blockquote class="border-l-2 border-[#d4af37] pl-4 py-2 my-8 italic text-[#d4af37]/80">Emma — Age 8 — (Jodelle Emma Walsh)</blockquote>
    <p class="mb-6">Okay so I have been telling my dad for literally years that something happened and he won't tell me what but I KNOW something happened because of several reasons that I have in a list in my head:<br>One. He runs every morning before anyone is awake and the running is not for fitness, Mum is right, because when he comes back from fitness running you feel good and when he comes back from this running he just looks tired in a different way.<br>Two. He does not go to Millhaven and he does not explain why. I asked once and he said we just don't and then he made pancakes, which is what he does when he is changing the subject and wants me to be distracted by something good, which works but I am eight not four.<br>Three. My middle name is Jodelle which is not a normal middle name and when I was little and asked about it he said it was someone important and that was the whole answer.<br>Four. There is a group chat on his phone called The Problem and it has been there my whole life and I have never seen him open it. I know it's there because I use his phone sometimes when mine is charging and it's just there, at the bottom, never updated, never gone.<br>Five. He cried once. He thought no one saw but I was on the stairs. He was in the kitchen by himself late at night and I don't know what he was thinking about but he was crying in the specific way adults cry when they've been not-crying for a long time and then they run out of not-crying. I went back upstairs. I didn't tell Mum.<br>So when we walked into the solicitor's waiting room and there were four other girls all named Jodelle I was like: OBVIOUSLY.<br>And then Sophie (who is thirteen and clearly the organized one) said we should wait until the camp to ask the big questions and I said okay because she is thirteen and I am eight and she probably knows more things.<br>But I already know some things.<br>Someone important died. All five of our dads or mums were there when she died. None of them have recovered from it properly. And somehow — this is the bit I can't figure out yet — we all got named after her.<br>I told Clara (the little one, she's five) some of this while the adults were talking in the car park.<br>"I know," Clara said.<br>"You're five," I said. "How do you know?"<br>She thought about this very seriously. "My dad looks at the trees sometimes," she said. "Like there's something there. I look too. There isn't anything. But he keeps looking." She paused. "I think he's looking for someone."<br>I thought about this.<br>"I think they all are," I said.<br>Clara nodded. "That's sad," she said.<br>"Yes," I said. "But I think the camp is supposed to fix it."<br>Clara looked at the car park. At our parents, standing in their cluster with their careful voices.<br>"I hope so," she said. "He's been sad a long time."</p>
    <div class="text-center text-[#d4af37]/40 my-8 tracking-widest">✦ ✦ ✦</div>
    <blockquote class="border-l-2 border-[#d4af37] pl-4 py-2 my-8 italic text-[#d4af37]/80">Jodi — Age 7 — (Jodelle, no middle name — Blake-Reina)</blockquote>
    <p class="mb-6">I want to be a detective.<br>Not a police detective — a private detective, like in the old films Mum shows me sometimes, where one person figures out everything that everyone else missed and then stands in a room and explains it calmly. I would be good at this because I notice things.<br>Here is what I noticed in the solicitor's waiting room:<br>All five adults were scared. Not of the will — of each other.<br>They walked in separately and when each new person came through the door the ones already there got very still in a specific way. The way you get still when something is about to happen and you're not sure if it's going to hurt.<br>My mum got still when she saw a man with dark hair (Sophie's dad, I figured out later). He got still too. They looked at each other for exactly two seconds and then they both looked somewhere else very deliberately, which is what people do when they don't want to look like they're not looking.<br>My mum makes films. She says the most important thing in a film is what people do when they think nobody's watching. I have been trained to watch people when they think nobody's watching.<br>All five of the adults, at different moments in the car park, glanced at each other when the other person wasn't looking. Each time: a look that contained too much. A look that had been stored for a long time and was leaking around the edges.<br>They were not glad to see each other. But they were something. Something that had no clean name.<br>Sophie said: we wait until the camp.<br>The camp. Two weeks in July, at a place called Camp Aldermoor, which is somewhere in the woods in northern Wisconsin. The solicitor told us outside while our parents talked.<br>I know about the camp. Mum has a brochure — an old one, worn soft at the creases, in a box in her closet where she keeps the things she doesn't want me to see but hasn't been able to throw away. I found it two years ago when I was looking for my Halloween costume.<br>On the cover: a lake. Pine trees. Blue sky. CAMP ALDERMOOR — Senior Leadership Program.<br>I put it back exactly where I found it. I didn't say anything.<br>But now I know where we're going.<br>And I think — I think the brochure in my mum's closet is not random. I think she kept it because going back there is the thing she has needed to do for a long time and has been too scared to do.<br>So she's sending us instead.<br>Interesting.</p>
    <div class="text-center text-[#d4af37]/40 my-8 tracking-widest">✦ ✦ ✦</div>
    <p class="mb-6">
    <blockquote class="border-l-2 border-[#d4af37] pl-4 py-2 my-8 italic text-[#d4af37]/80">Clara — Age 5 — (Jodelle Clara Park)</blockquote><br>My dad builds things.<br>He draws buildings on paper first — a lot of paper, covered in lines — and then real people build them from the drawings, which means the drawings have to be exactly right or the building will be wrong. He says this is very serious work and I believe him because he looks serious when he does it, but he also sometimes smiles at his drawings in a way that means he loves them.<br>He is very careful. He checks things a lot. When we go somewhere new he walks around it first and looks at all the parts before we go in. I do this too. I don't know if I learned it from him or if we're just the same.<br>In the solicitor's waiting room I looked at the water cooler for a while because it made a sound every four minutes and I wanted to know if it was exactly four minutes or approximately four minutes. (Approximately. Sometimes three minutes and fifty-eight seconds, sometimes four minutes and three seconds. This told me it was a mechanical process, not a digital one.)<br>The other girls were interesting.<br>Emma talked the most. She thinks fast and talks at the same speed, which means she says true things before she's decided whether to say them. I liked this.<br>Meera was careful, like my dad, but faster. She looks at everything the way I look at the water cooler — what is the pattern, why does it do that. I think we would get along.<br>Jodi watched everyone watching each other and then explained what the watching meant. This is a useful skill.<br>Sophie was the oldest and she organized the rest of us without making it feel like organizing. She decided we would wait until camp. This seemed right. You don't ask questions in the wrong place — you wait for the place where the answers live.<br>I know a little about the camp because my dad keeps the brochure under some other papers on his desk. He doesn't know I know. I didn't read it carefully — I was four when I found it — but I remember the picture. A lake. Trees. Blue sky.<br>And I know the camp is in the woods. And I know my dad looks at the treeline sometimes, in the backyard, in the evenings.<br>I look too, when he's not watching me look.<br>I don't know what I'm looking for.<br>But I think the woods might know.</p>
    <div class="text-center text-[#d4af37]/40 my-8 tracking-widest">✦ ✦ ✦</div>
    
</div>`
