      title: "Arrival",
      synopsis: "",
      text: `<div class="reading-font text-gray-300">
    
    <blockquote class="border-l-2 border-[#d4af37] pl-4 py-2 my-8 italic text-[#d4af37]/80">Sophie, 13</blockquote>
    <p class="mb-6">The van from Millhaven to Camp Aldermoor took three hours, and I spent most of them watching the road narrow.<br>Four lanes. Two lanes. State route. Forestry road. ALDERMOOR 4MI in reflective letters.<br>I’ve read enough to know that when a story returns to a place, the place is never the same. The landscape is identical but the meaning has shifted — everything the same and nothing the same. I thought about this as the trees got denser and the road got less interested in being a road.
    <br>In the van with us: a camp staff member named Bex, who was twenty-something with paint-stained fingers and the easy warmth of someone who genuinely likes children and doesn’t need anyone to think they’re cool. She told us about the camp in the way people tell you about places they love — specific, unhurried, with the particular details that only someone who has been there in all weather knows.<br>“The lake is really cold,” she said. “Even in July. It’s glacial. Clear, though — you can see all the way to the bottom in the shallows.”<br>“Who named the camp?” Meera asked. She had her notebook open.<br>“It was named for the territory. Aldermoor is an old name — it means alder marsh. Alder trees. There’s a wetland on the north side that’s been there a very long time.”<br>“How old is the camp?” Meera asked.<br>“Established 1987,” Bex said. “But the land is much older. There was a forestry operation here before — you’ll actually learn about that as part of the program. The camp has a history curriculum built into it. The land has a history.”
    <br>Meera looked at me. I looked at Meera.<br>Neither of us said anything.<br>The gate appeared — wooden, carved letters, solar lights. The gravel road. The horseshoe of cabins. The lake beyond.<br>Clara pressed her face against the window.<br>“The trees are older on that side,” she said. To herself, mostly. She was pointing west, at the tree line beyond the camp’s managed boundary.<br>I looked at the western tree line. Dense. Tall. Old.<br>“How do you know?” Bex said.<br>“The shape of the canopy,” Clara said. “And the color. Old trees are a different green.”<br>Bex looked at her — a child of five making a dendrology observation — with an expression that was both surprised and something else. Something that acknowledged without naming.<br>“You’re right,” she said. “Those are old growth. Pre-camp.”<br>Clara nodded, like this was what she expected.<br>Emma leaned over to me. “She’s five,” she whispered.<br>“I know,” I whispered back.<br>The van stopped. We climbed out. The air was different here — heavy, cool, pine-specific. The lake was silver between the trees.<br>I stood on the gravel and looked at the camp. At the horseshoe of cabins around the lodge. At the western tree line. At the low wooden fence that marked the boundary between the managed land and whatever was beyond it.<br>Something about the fence.<br>Something about the western tree line.<br>Something I didn’t have the information yet to name.<br>I filed it. I was good at filing things.<br>“Sophie,” Bex said. She was looking at me with the specific look adults use when they’ve been told to look for someone. “You’re in Cabin Seven. All five of you — you’ve been assigned together.”<br>Together. On the same team.<br>Not an accident.<br>“Okay,” I said. “Thank you.”<br>I picked up my bag and walked toward Cabin Seven and thought: something is waiting here. Something was left here and has been waiting for the right people to come and find it.
    <br>We were the right people.<br>We just didn’t know yet what we were finding.</p>
</div>`
