      title: "The Other Campers (And the Thing About the West)",
      synopsis: "",
      text: `<div class="reading-font text-gray-300">
    
    <blockquote class="border-l-2 border-[#d4af37] pl-4 py-2 my-8 italic text-[#d4af37]/80">Emma, 8</blockquote>
    <p class="mb-6">Camp Aldermoor had thirty kids in it this summer. The others were from all over — some from nearby, some from further, some who knew each other and some who didn’t. We were the only group that had arrived together with the specific purposefulness of people on a mission.<br>(Sophie told us not to make it obvious we were on a mission. I told her I was eight and knew how to be subtle. She did not look fully convinced.)<br>The other campers were mostly fine. There was a girl named Harriet who was ten and had very decided opinions about card games. There was a pair of twins named Olu and Kemi who did everything in parallel in a way that was somehow not annoying. There was a quiet boy named Fletcher who read constantly and whom Meera had already identified as a potential ally.<br>The counselor in charge of our group was Bex, which I was glad about because Bex was clearly someone who took children seriously, which not all adults do.
    <br>But the most interesting thing about the first day wasn’t any of the other campers.<br>It was the man at orientation.<br>His name was Mr. Hargreave.<br>Not the solicitor — a different Hargreave. Related, maybe. He was older — maybe sixty-five, maybe seventy — and he ran the camp’s trust, Bex explained. He came to the opening orientation every summer to say a few words about the camp’s history and purpose.<br>He said the words. They were about the land, about the history of the territory, about the forestry station that had operated here before the camp. He said the name Kellerman — the Kellerman Forestry Station, established 1923, abandoned 1954 — with the ease of someone who has said it many times.<br>And then he looked at us.<br>Not at the group. At the five of us.<br>A look that lasted approximately three seconds and said something I couldn’t translate yet but that I was going to.<br>I wrote in my notebook (I had started a notebook, like Meera; it felt necessary): Hargreave — the solicitor’s office and the camp are connected. He knows who we are.<br>Meera, next to me, had written the same thing in her notebook in different words.<br>After orientation, the other kids dispersed to get settled and explore. Sophie gathered us by the fence at the western boundary. The five of us, standing in a row, looking through the fence at the old growth beyond.<br>“The camp was built on top of something older,” Sophie said. “The treasure hunt — which starts day three — is designed around the land’s history. The Kellerman Forestry Station. Something out there.” She looked through the fence. “We find what our parents found.”<br>“And then what?” Jodi said.<br>“I don’t know,” Sophie said. “We find out what we need to know and then we understand what they need to tell us.”<br>“They can’t tell us,” Meera said. “They’ve never been able to.”<br>“Maybe,” Sophie said, “they don’t have to. Maybe it’s here. Already here, waiting for us to find it.”
    <br>We stood at the fence and looked at the old growth.<br>Clara was looking at a specific point between two birch trees. Two birch trees that had grown together at the base, their trunks leaning apart and then back toward each other, forming an arch.<br>She was quiet for a long moment.<br>"That's an old place," she said. Not pointing, not alarmed. Just — noting it, the way she noted the water cooler's rhythm in the solicitor's office. "Something was there for a very long time."<br>"Something like what?" I said.<br>She thought about it with the seriousness she gave all questions. "Something that waited," she said. "I don't know for what." She looked at the arch for another moment. "It's still waiting."<br>We all looked at the birch arch.<br>Dark between the trunks. The forest interior. Nothing moving.<br>"How do you know?" Sophie said. She asked it carefully, the way you ask a five year old something you actually want the answer to.<br>Clara looked at her. "Places feel different when something important happened in them," she said. "Like a room after an argument. Even if you weren't there for the argument you can still feel it." She turned away from the fence. "That place had something important in it. Maybe it still does."<br>Nobody said anything for a moment.<br>"Okay," Sophie said quietly. "Then we find it."</p>
</div>`
