      text: `<div class="reading-font text-gray-300">
       <blockquote class="border-l-2 border-[#d4af37] pl-4 py-2 my-8 italic text-[#d4af37]/80">Meera, 9</blockquote>
    <p class="mb-6">I started mapping the camp on the first morning.<br>Not because anyone told me to. Because mapping is how I understand spaces — where things are relative to each other, what’s at the center and what’s at the edges. I do it everywhere. Mum says I’ve been doing it since I was four.<br>The camp was mappable. It had a logic — the horseshoe of cabins around the lodge, the lake to the east, the managed forest on three sides, the old growth to the west beyond the fence. The trail system was marked with colored blazes on the trees. I copied the trail map and added my own annotations.<br>By the end of the first day I had a working map of the camp.<br>By the end of the second day I had begun to extend it. Past the fence, based on what I could observe from the ridge and the lakeshore, and based on the historical topographic map that was framed on the wall of the camp office, which I asked Bex permission to study and which she gave me, looking at me with an expression I was beginning to recognize as you are not the first person to do this.<br>I noted: the framed historical map showed a structure approximately four hundred meters west-northwest of the fence. A building, marked KELLERMAN FS STATION — MAIN BLDG. With a small annotation: NE corner — time capsule, 1953.<br>I showed this to Sophie.<br>She looked at it for a long time.<br>“The treasure hunt,” she said.<br>“Yes,” I said. “I think that’s what it’s designed around. The Kellerman Station. The time capsule. The northeast corner.”<br>“Our parents found it,” Sophie said.<br>“Yes,” I said. “And I think we’re meant to find it too.”<br>The treasure hunt started on day three. The clues were clever — they pointed to things on camp property, progressively older, building toward something. Day one: a twin tree. Day two: a spring. Day three: a standing stone with a carved arrow.<br>Each clue pointed west.<br>Each clue pointed toward something older than the camp.
    <br>I updated my map every evening, in the cabin, while the others talked or read or slept. Sophie would come and sit beside me and look at it without speaking, which I found comfortable rather than intrusive — she was looking at it the way you look at something you are trying to understand, not the way people look at things they’re performing interest in.<br>By day five my map had a dotted line. The dotted line began at the camp’s center and extended northwest, through each clue location, through the fence, through the old growth, terminating at the Kellerman Station foundation.<br>“That’s the pattern,” Sophie said.<br>“Yes,” I said. “The hunt is tracing a path. To the foundation. To the northeast corner.”<br>“The time capsule is in the county archive,” Sophie said. “I looked it up.” She had a phone — we all had phones for emergencies, confiscated every night by Bex and returned in the morning. Sophie had used hers efficiently. “Removed in 2012 by the county historical trust. The contents are documented. Maps, field notes, a letter. The letter was written by Elias Kellerman.”<br>“Who was Elias Kellerman?” Emma said. She had been listening — she always listened, even when she looked like she wasn’t.<br>“The last man to work the station,” Sophie said. “He was seventy-one when it closed. He buried the time capsule a year before.” She paused. “He died in 1961.”<br>“Then what’s in the northeast corner now?” Jodi said.<br>“That’s what our parents found,” Sophie said. “The camp’s treasure hunt cache. Put there by the hunt designers to be found.” She looked at my map. “Something worth finding. That’s what the camp says about it.”<br>“They always say that,” Bex said, from the doorway.<br>We all turned.<br>She was standing in the cabin doorway with her paint-stained fingers and her easy warmth, and she was looking at us with an expression that was absolutely not the expression of someone who had accidentally overheard. It was the expression of someone who had been waiting for the right moment.<br>“Come with me,” she said. “All five of you. Mr. Hargreave would like to talk to you.”</p>
</div>`  
